All lifetable summary indices are functions of age, but these are usually only calculated for age zero, or sometimes the age at maturity, retirement, or some other particular age. We propose to let lifetable summary measures be calculated at all ages, thereby producing age patterns to summary measures. We provide some elementary definitions of functions described and derived from the conditional lifespan distribution, and we apply these to Swedish females from the Human Mortality Database (HMD).

Certain lifecourse decisions are made with a kind of forward-looking anticipation of one's own mortality, especially estate planning and related decisions. Typically, the educated guesser refers to the survival curve or the remaining life expectancy at a particular age. This might be an adequate summary of information in most instances, but in some instances we ought to account for the full spread of potential outcomes over age. Why? Because different outcomes may have different costs and payoffs for individuals (and families), and these may not average out as parsimoniously as life expectancy (which is just a mean).

In this poster we've provided a glimpse of some of the demography that might prove useful for the calculation of a full age pattern of a hypothetical payoff. This work is still in progress, and we've not yet explored the details of applications. Payoffs could be evolutionary, financial, or some other value functioned on survival, such as kinship networks.
